  "response_text": "Inflation in an economy can be caused by several factors, and it often results from a combination of these factors. Here are some of the primary causes:\n\n1. **Demand-Pull Inflation**: This occurs when aggregate demand in the economy exceeds aggregate supply. When consumers, businesses, and the government collectively spend more than what is produced, prices tend to rise as goods and services become scarcer relative to demand.\n\n2. **Cost-Push Inflation**: This happens when the cost of production inputs (like raw materials, labor, or energy) increases, leading businesses to raise their selling prices to maintain profit margins. Higher input costs can also lead to wage demands from workers, which can further increase costs for businesses.\n\n3. **Built-In Inflation**: This concept suggests that inflation becomes self-sustaining due to expectations and wage-price spirals. If people expect prices to continue rising, they may demand higher wages to keep up with those rising prices, which in turn leads businesses to raise prices",
